{{mil-stub}}

'''Sinhalisation''' is a term, derived from [[Sinhala (disambiguation)|Sinhala]], that has number of meanings in [[Sri Lanka]].
==Sociological== In a sociological context it could refer to the [[cultural assimilation|assimilation]] of ethno-cultural minorities in Sri Lanka such as the [[Sri Lankan Tamils]], [[Colombo Chetties]] and indigenous [[Vedda people|Vedda]]s into the majority Sinhalese identity,<ref>Susantha Goonetilleke, ''Sinhalisation: Migration or Cultural Colonization?'' Lanka Guardian Vol. 3, No. I, May I, 1980, pp. 22-29, and May 15 1980, pp. 18-19.</ref> including some Sinhala Buddhists of the interior such as the [[Demalagattara]] and some Catholics such as the [[Bharatha]] of the coastal areas of the [[island nation]].<ref>Power and Religiosity in a Post-Colonial Setting: Sinhala Catholics in Contemporary Sri Lanka by R. L. Stirrat American Ethnologist, Vol. 22, No. 2 (May, 1995), pp. 428-429</ref><ref name="Betrayed">[https://books.google.com/books?id=3MO_86VwNSkC&pg=PA1&lpg=PA1&dq=Buddhism+Betrayed?:+Religion,+Politics,+and+Violence+in+Sri+Lanka#v=onepage&q=rice-farming&f=false/ Buddhism Betrayed?: Religion, Politics, and Violence in Sri Lanka By Stanley Jeyaraja Tambiah, p. 152-3]</ref><ref>[http://lakdiva.org/codrington/chap01.html A SHORT HISTORY OF LANKA by Humphry William Codrington, CHAPTER I; THE BEGINNINGS 'The princess and her retinue/dowry (service castes)']</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=9PiwJF7V4EQC&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=Pandyan+retinue+of+prince+vijaya&source=bl&ots=CF6Q1zNCFG&sig=ep_Xjrp_vrGi5bPnwl1RCvuajWY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=TV5JU_yOCu6O7QbQwID4Dw&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA#v=snippet&q=Prince%20Vijaya&f=false 'Pandyan retinue of Prince Vijaya': Sea: Our Saviour By K. Sridharan, p.19]</ref><ref>[http://www.island.lk/2008/07/20/features14.html Pre-Vijayan Agriculture in Sri Lanka, by Prof. T. W. Wikramanayake]</ref><ref name="Kshatriya">{{cite journal | pmid = 8543296 | volume=67 | title=Genetic affinities of Sri Lankan populations | date=December 1995 | journal=Hum. Biol. | pages=843–66 | last1 = Kshatriya | first1 = GK}}</ref><ref name="Ranaweera">[http://www.nature.com/jhg/journal/v59/n1/full/jhg2013112a.html Mitochondrial DNA history of Sri Lankan ethnic people: their relations within the island and with the Indian subcontinental populations, L Ranaweera, et al; Journal of Human Genetics (2014)]</ref>
Many noted elite {{cref|elite}} families of foreign origins were supposedly Sinhalised during the pre-[[colony|colonial period]].<ref>"History of the Colombo Chetties" by Deshabandu Reggie Candappa published in December, 2000</ref><ref>[http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~lkawgw/gen3146.html Pilimatalavuva - Family], roots.web, Accessed 13-06-2015</ref> (see [http://sundaytimes.lk/010708/plus6.html abstract here])
==Political== In a political context it could refer to the [[Sinhala Only Act|Sinhala language-favouring policies]] {{cref|PS}}of the post colonial governments of Sri Lanka that is considered to be a major cause <ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.paradisepoisoned.com/PDFs/Preview21.pdf |title= How it Came to This – Learning from Sri Lanka’s Civil Wars By Professor John Richardson|accessdate=2006-03-30 |format= |work=paradisepoisoned.com}}</ref> of the [[Sri Lankan civil war]]. It is termed as culturo-ideological [[exclusivism]] by some{{who|date=July 2014}} when one's cultural values and norms are absolutised in such a manner that a particular way of life is enshrined as superior to all others and must therefore be adopted by others (e.g. the [[Sri Lankan Tamil|Tamil]] reaction to the perceived "Sinhalisation" processes of the Sri Lankan state)<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.wcc-coe.org/wcc/what/faith/kuala-docs13-makarios.pdf |title= Ethnic Identity, National Identity and the Search for Unity|accessdate=2006-03-30 |format= |work=World Council of Churches}}</ref>
It was said to be a cause of the abortive coup by disgruntled Catholic army officers in [[1962 Ceylonese coup d'état attempt|1962]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.hindustantimes.in/news/7752_1708229,004100180006.htm |title= Significance of the abortive 1962 military coup|accessdate=2006-03-30 |work=Hindustan Times}}</ref>
Currently some observers note that Sri Lankan political parties such as [[Jathika Hela Urumaya|JHU]] and [[Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna|JVP]] adhere to a policy of political Sinhalisation.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.uthr.org/Briefings/Briefing6.htm |title= The Human Rights and Humanitarian Fallout from the Sri Lankan Government’s Eastern Agenda and the LTTE's Obduracy|accessdate=2006-03-30 |work=[[UTHR]]}}</ref>
==Other Meanings== Medias use the word "Sinhalisation" to refer to the process by which the Sri Lankan government funded and sponsored settlement of Sinhala people in Tamil-dominant regions in order to make Tamil as minorities. Some reports claims that the Sinhalese and Sinhala military families are settled in houses built by money from the Indian government that was intended to improve the welfare of the Tamil people.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?catid=13&artid=36250 |title= TamilNet: 23.04.13 Indian news magazine highlights accelerated Sinhalization of Tamil north|accessdate=2013-04-23 |work=[[UTHR]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theweekendleader.com/Causes/615/Exclusive:-Inside-Lanka.html |title= Exclusive: Erasing the cultural leftover of Tamils to convert Sri Lanka into Sinhala country|accessdate=2013-04-23 |work=[[UTHR]]}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lankanewsweb.com/english/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3359:-new-military-colonies-in-murukandi-sinhalization-in-puthumathalan&catid=1:general&Itemid=29 |title= New military colonies in Murukandi; Sinhalization in Puthumathalan|accessdate=2013-04-23 |work=[[UTHR]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lankanewspapers.com/news/2012/3/75428_space.html |title= Salt on Old Wounds: The systematic Sinhalization of Sri Lanka`s North, East, the historic habitat of the Tamil speaking people |accessdate=2013-04-23 |work=[[UTHR]]}}</ref>
==Notes== {{refbegin}} <!-- See [[Template:cref]] and [[Template:cnote]] for an explanation of how to create content notes for this section --> {{cnote|elite|The late President [[J. R. Jayewardene]]'s first paternal ancestor was a Colombo Chetty and there is an excerpt from the biography of J.R., authored by Prof. K.M. De Silva & Howard Wriggins, in support of this. Don Adrian Jayewardene, J.R.'s paternal great-grandfather, descended from a Chetty family, but two or three generations earlier, a male of this family had married a Sinhalese by the name of Jayewardene from the village of Walgama near Hanwella and had taken on the name of Jayewardene and by the time Don Adrian arrived on the scene at the tail-end of the 18th century, ''the process of 'Sinhalisation' of his family had been completed.''[http://sundaytimes.lk/010708/plus6.html]}}
{{cnote|PS|Sri Lanka’s nation-building programme became intimately linked with a Sinhalisation of the state directive. It was expected that the [[minorities]] would be assimilated into this new [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]] [[Buddhist]] nation-state. Moreover, the 1956 election marked the beginning of an era of ethnically-based party politics. [http://www.brad.ac.uk/acad/confres/assets/CCR2.pdf]}}
{{refend}}
